Three cheetah cubs born in Iran
World's fastest animal falls victim to brutal hunting, droughts and deadly car crashes across the Islamic Republic
This resulted in fewer than 20 cheetahs falling in number.
Three Asian cheetah cubs recently emerged into the world's air in the Islamic Republic of Iran.
It's a rare birth that only slightly improves the endangered animal's status in the country due to droughts, hunters and fatal car crashes.
This is the first birth of a cheetah in captivity in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in nature.
Iranian news agency IRNA said the veterinary team, which trusts Thoran National Park in the northern province of Semnan, decided on a captive birth.
It also noted that fewer than 20 cheetahs have been recorded in seven different provinces of the country in recent times.
Due to the threat of extinction, the United Nations implemented a defence plan for them back in 2001.
Now, Iran is hoping the new puppies can bring about cheetah population growth in the future.
In January, Iran's deputy environment minister Hassan Akbari said the country's cheetah population had dramatically decreased from 100 in 2010.
"Their situation is extremely serious," Akbari said, noting that cheetahs have fallen victim to drought in their habitat, hunting and even car accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest animal in the world capable of reaching speeds of about 100 km / h.
Cheetahs can be found in various places across the globe, from India to Senegal in West Africa.
